note.body:
I'm so sorry. I found that this is not a bug with tinysparql at all but a problem with archlinux. 🥲🥲🥲

See also [archlinux tinysparql/Issues/#2](https://gitlab.archlinux.org/archlinux/packaging/packages/tinysparql/-/issues/2). Arch Linux maintainers recently [changed the version control method from git tag to manually specified commit hash](https://gitlab.archlinux.org/archlinux/packaging/packages/tinysparql/-/commit/4ca042ca9ae5de85b15f1e573b3b993284e240b6). However, they didn't update the commit hash for subsequent updates. So actually it's still stuck at 3.8.0 instead of 3.8.2.

Because it's hard to notice the wrong commit hash used in the build script, I didn't find it until today. This issue is actually solved in !730, I've verified on loong64 platform that it works well now.

I apologize again for the confusion caused to you. 😖

note.body:
> Is there a reason we can't just build the docs from source during the build? I believe that's what other GNOME projects that use gi-docgen do.

Originally it was because I didn't want to ship gi-docgen as a submodule and double tarball size.

Later it was because we still preferred to avoid `dot` and `xmlto` dependencies for other than developers if possible.

And this gitlab issue is not a convincing argument for it to change, since you are finding trouble with "just building the docs". As said, the issue is in your setup, there has been no substantial changes in this setup between 3.7 and 3.8, other than catering for TinySPARQL being built as a meson submodule, and the existing build instructions cannot result in the fallout you describe.

> I prefer to build from the tarball but I remove `docs/reference/libtracker-sparql/doc` to ensure I build the docs from source. This worked automatically for tracker 3.7.3 but doesn't work for tinysparql 3.8 beta or 3.8.1.

You found the trick to have docs rebuilt, I'm afraid you'll need to find out too why `docs/reference/libtracker-sparql/install-devhelp.sh` as called from `docs/reference/libtracker-sparql/meson.build` does result in `$srcdir/docs/reference/libtracker-sparql/` copied instead of `$builddir/docs/reference/libtracker-sparql/docs` as generated by gi-docgen, because that will never happen with the script and meson instructions as included in the tarball.

I tried downloading the last available tarball, deleting the pre-generated doc dir as you instructed, building and installing. `$datadir/doc/Tsparql-3.0/` is still the only copied location with no leftover files, and it contains the correct generated docs. So there does seem to be more to it unrelated to the tarball and the described step.

target_title: Add build option for webide

note.body:
Hey Jeremy,

Thanks for raising this.

We thought a lot about how best to ship the web IDE. My main requirement was that we do not want any internet access happening during `meson configure` or `meson build`. So the best tradeoff was to have a separate build process for the web IDE that runs before `meson configure`. And to simplify things further we committed the output of this build process to Git.

We are using npm to pull the dependencies and I'm guessing this already has a command to produce the copyright and license info for all the dependencies. If it's not possible to run `npm` during downstream package builds, we could include the steps in the upstream build process and commit the necessary metadata alongside the dist.js file so you can process it downstream.

The code [is not minimized in the dist.js file](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/tinysparql/-/blob/main/src/web-ide/dist/main.js?ref_type=heads). If you look at the `eval()` statements created by WebPack you'll see the actual source code of each dependency, untranslated. We like being able to debug things :-)

What do other Debian packages do around including stuff from NPM ? If there's something we can do upstream to make this easier to package then i'm happy to do it. But I prefer that we don't end up with it disabled by default.

> My understanding is that the webide feature is more of a developer tool and wouldn't be needed by most people who only have tinysparql installed because it is a component of the GNOME desktop.

It is a developer tool but we do want it to be easily accessible. The search infra in GNOME is critically undermaintained, so the idea here is to make it easier for new developers to get involved and see how it works. We really want to be able to say to someone "run $command in a terminal to start the SPARQL web IDE".

If you do split it into a separate package, that's reasonable, but our "how to open the web IDE" documentation now has to have a Debian/Ubuntu specific section, so it's better for us if it can be part of the main tinysparql package.

target_title: Bail on batch use in python

note.body:
FTR here, I assume that these commands in gdb, on a running process:

```
(gdb) frame 5
(gdb) call g_type_name(value->g_type)
```

Will return something like "GValue", because the `add_statement()` method in python (in C it's called `tracker_batch_add_statementv()`) will already know to collect python types/objects, and wrap them as GValues for the C code to interpret, and you are passing GValues, so the TinySPARQL code will see GValues containing GValues which it doesn't know how to handle.

Thanks to the python GI sugar, you can avoid creating GValues yourself completely, and pass an array of python things to this function, e.g. `[self.props.pl_id, float(old), float(new)]`, that should work as expected.
